{"key":"processedPost-10737245","value":{"id":10737245,"first":10734703,"last":10737245,"when":1248535541,"utime":"07/25/09 06:25 PM","cleanedPost":"<blockquote>Quote:<br />what if i didn't drill holes on the bottom and floated a tray with my perlite and cakes on an inch or two of water? This way i would be able to increase my humidity. </blockquote><br />Wrong.<br />It would lower humidity.&nbsp; As said above, perlite works due to the very high surface area that evaporates moisture.&nbsp; With standing water, you only have a flat surface area the size of the tub.&nbsp; With perlite, you have a thousand or more times that much area, thus much higher humidity.<br />In addition, humidity isn't the most important pinning trigger.&nbsp; Fresh air is.&nbsp; Shoot for the maximum amount of fresh air possible, and then mist as required to make up for humidity.<br />RR"}}